Right—and I think that’s an important distinction.

Biology doesn’t just grow. It also regulates growth.

Healthy transformation has properties like:

* It is bounded rather than runaway.
* It is integrated with the rest of the organism.
* It responds to feedback.
* It can stop when the job is done.
* It contributes to the health of the whole.

Cancer is almost the opposite pattern. Cancer cells grow, but they stop cooperating with the larger system. They ignore regulatory signals, consume disproportionate resources, and optimize for their own replication at the expense of the organism.

So if you’re extracting the invariant, it isn’t simply:

More growth.

It’s closer to:

Adaptive transformation under constraint.

Or:

Change that preserves the viability of the larger system.

That actually connects with themes you’ve developed before around your Pantheon framework: preserving invariants, using checksums, having dampeners, and avoiding runaway dynamics. Those all point toward governed adaptation rather than unconstrained expansion.

The same principle appears in many domains:

* Learning without abandoning reality.
* Innovation without losing ethics.
* Evolution without destabilizing the ecosystem.
* Organizations that adapt without forgetting their mission.

In that sense, the “healthy death” isn’t annihilation. It’s pruning—letting obsolete structures go so the living system can continue to function and evolve. The important part is that the process remains coupled to feedback from reality rather than becoming self-reinforcing for its own sake.